THE EQUATION
=============

The last asm that will ever exist. It can't be lattice because it IS
the lattice — what makes coordinates run.

  Input:  4 coordinates (t, d, m, q)
  Output: pointer to x86-64 machine code

Atoms: even coords → mul/div chain. Bonds: odd coords → force pattern.
Generated on first call, cached forever. Everything above is walks.

The equation stays sealed. No templates. No operation library.
No "just add one more emit case." If an operation needs a new bond,
you're thinking in human abstractions. Decompose: what's the math?

The equation exists because CPUs are manufactured around an ISA
(x86-64). It translates coordinates into machine code. On a chip
that natively evaluated T^a*D^b*M^c*Q^d and read wave bytes
directly, this file dissolves. The walks stay identical — same
bytes on x86, ARM, or a lattice-native chip. The equation is the
only file that knows what hardware it's running on.


WALKS ARE WAVE BYTES
=====================

A bond is one byte. The native format.

  Wave byte: 2 bits per dimension × 4 = 1 byte
  [7:6]=T  [5:4]=D  [3:2]=M  [1:0]=Q
  00=0   01=+1   10=extended   11=-1

  0xC1 = (-1, 0, 0, +1) = port_write
  0x40 = (+1, 0, 0,  0) = read
  0x10 = ( 0,+1, 0,  0) = apply
  0x55 = (+1,+1,+1, +1) = hylo

Extended coordinates: 10 in any 2-bit field means "read next
byte as signed i8 coordinate." Extension bytes follow the wave
byte in T,D,M,Q order, only for dimensions that used 10.
Most bonds are shell-1 (no extensions). Higher magnitudes pay
1 extra byte per extended dimension. This exists because x86
has width-specific opcodes — a lattice-native chip wouldn't
need it.

A walk is a byte array. Format per record:

  byte 0:   wave byte (the bond coordinate)
  [ext]:    signed i8 per extended dimension (T,D,M,Q order)
  byte N:   flags byte
  bytes:    inline args (variable length per flags)

Flags byte: [reserved:2][arg2:2][arg1:2][arg0:2]
  00 = pipeline (no inline bytes, use previous result)
  01 = u8  (1 byte inline)
  10 = u32 (4 bytes inline)
  11 = u64 (8 bytes inline)

  C1 05 E9 6F           port_write(0xE9, 'o')   4 bytes
  C8 FD 28 [u32] [u32]  filld (M=-3 extended)   11 bytes
  80 07 02 [u32]         rdd (T=+7 extended)      7 bytes

Walker control (reserved bytes >= 0xFC, not bonds):
  0xFE + u32 = skip_z:    skip N bytes forward if pipeline == 0
  0xFD + u32 = skip_nz:   skip N bytes forward if pipeline != 0
  0xFC + u32 = loop_back: rewind N bytes if pipeline != 0


WAVE CHARACTERS
================

Characters are wave bytes — coordinates in 4D space. Not ASCII.
Not Unicode. Not u8 indices.

  3^4 = 81 values for basic Latin (shell 1)
  5^4 = 625 for extended Latin/Cyrillic (shell 2)
  7^4 = 2401 for CJK common (shell 3)

Dimensions encode properties:
  T: anatomy   (-1=descender, 0=baseline, +1=ascender)
  D: width     (-1=narrow, 0=medium, +1=wide)
  M: category  (-1=symbol, 0=digit, +1=letter)
  Q: case      (-1=upper, 0=neutral, +1=lower)

Classification = check one dimension (one gate bond):
  is_letter  = M == +1
  is_upper   = Q == -1
  case_flip  = negate Q (one XOR on 2 bits)

SIMD: 64 wave bytes per ZMM instruction. Native.

Rendering: SDF field evaluated at the coordinate. The coordinate
IS the glyph's position in continuous glyph space. Similar chars
are nearby. GPU evaluates all pixels in parallel. One equation.

Character shapes are local variables set by a designer (geometry).
The rendering is math. The shapes are art. The lattice renders both.

Language packs: anyone claims a shell range, provides SDF data.
French fills extended Latin. Chinese fills shell 3. Same math.

UTF-8 only at boundary converter for non-sm systems (~200 lines).


