TRACE PIPELINE — HOW WALKS USE TRACES
========================================

The foundational primitive. Everything above traces depends on this.

Trace read (~10 bonds, all existing operations):

  read(trace + WCURSOR)     → pipeline = write_cursor
  write(stash, pipeline)    → save write_cursor
  read(trace + RCURSOR)     → pipeline = read_cursor
  test(pipeline, stash)     → 1 if equal (empty), 0 if has data
  skip_nz                   → skip read path if empty (pipeline=1)
  AND(pipeline, mask)       → slot index
  atom DM(pipeline, recsz)  → byte offset (slot × record_size)
  add(buf_addr, pipeline)   → slot address
  read(pipeline)            → the data
  write(trace+RCURSOR, +1)  → advance read cursor

Trace write (symmetric): check full (write - read >= depth),
compute write slot, write data, advance write cursor.

Stash: BSS variable (stash_a). Single-core for now. Multi-core
needs per-trace scratch in reserved bytes [48:63] or core-local
memory.


TRACE REGISTRY
===============

Fixed array in BSS. Genesis writes it.

  trace_list:   resq MAX_TRACES    (each entry = trace address)
  trace_count:  resq 1

A core's "find work" walk: scan trace_list, read each trace's
cursors, compute fill (write - read, one subtract), pick fullest.
Read + compare + loop over known addresses.

